<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-748-864  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 748 864.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 13 1990 v7 n32 p44(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Filescapes ships UNIX-based archiving system. (Filescapes Corp.'sClasseur document management system) (Connectivity) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Filescapes Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Filescapes Classeur (Document processing system) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionDocument Management SystemsTurnkey Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;Offering users a dual approach to achieving the paperless office, FilescapesCorp. recently released a turnkey Unix-based image- and text-managementsystem and began an off-site document-archiving service.andM;The company's Classeur document-management system mirrors the features ofmany other recent market entries: It is a Unix-based system that providesusers with more hardware flexibility than the larger, proprietary systemsthat long defined the image-management business, said Stan Ching, presidentof Filescapes.andM;But the company is taking its image-management strategy a step further byalso offering a document-archiving service that moves the burdens of documentscanning and system maintenance from the customer to Filescapes.andM;Classeur is centered around a Sun Microsystems Inc. server running Unix andis equipped with an optical disk and Filescapes' Sybase Structured QueryLanguage-based querying system.andP;  It includes software designed to let RISCworkstation users retrieve scanned documents based on keywords in a profileof each document.andP;  It also includes software that lets remote users equippedwith a modem retrieve and view documents as if they were local.andM;The price of the Classeur network system, including the Sun server, three Sunworkstations, a scanner, an optical disk, software, installation andtraining, is approximately $135,000.andM;The first Classeur installation, at Sherman Oaks Community Hospital inCalifornia, is using the network to replace an off-site document storage andretrieval service to which it subscribed.andM;&quot;The [retrieval service's] price is going up, and it takes them a long timeto retrieve the information,&quot; said Bockhi Park, the hospital's director ofpatient information systems.andP;  &quot;This is less expensive and quicker.&quot;andM;For users who want to do away with paper documents while avoiding an on-sitenetwork entirely, Filescapes will convert to disk and store a minimum of1,000 pages of paper documents for 22 cents per page.andP;  Subscribers to theservice can retrieve documents for 22 cents per page, plus a $3 fee for eachrequest.andP;  Retrieved documents are sent by courier or fax to the customer onthe same day they are requested.andM;Filescapes, located in Calabasas, Calif., can be reached at (818) 794-6814.andO;</TEXT></DOC>